						<!-- firstHeading -->
			<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en"><span dir="auto"><i>Crucifixion and Last Judgement diptych</i></span></h1>
			<!-- /firstHeading -->
			<!-- bodyContent -->
			<div id="bodyContent">
								<!-- tagline -->
				<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
				<!-- /tagline -->
								<!-- subtitle -->
				<div id="contentSub"></div>
				<!-- /subtitle -->
																<!-- jumpto -->
				<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-head">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<!-- /jumpto -->
								<!-- bodycontent -->
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:412px;"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Jan_van_Eyck_-_Diptych_-_WGA07587.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Jan_van_Eyck_-_Diptych_-_WGA07587.jpg/410px-Jan_van_Eyck_-_Diptych_-_WGA07587.jpg" width="410" height="492" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Jan_van_Eyck_-_Diptych_-_WGA07587.jpg/615px-Jan_van_Eyck_-_Diptych_-_WGA07587.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Jan_van_Eyck_-_Diptych_-_WGA07587.jpg/820px-Jan_van_Eyck_-_Diptych_-_WGA07587.jpg 2x" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Jan_van_Eyck_-_Diptych_-_WGA07587.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="http://bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="Jan_van_Eyck" title="Jan van Eyck">Jan van Eyck</a>, <i>Crucifixion and Last Judgement diptych</i>, c. 1430–40. Oil on canvas, transferred from wood. Each 56.5&#160;cm × 19.7&#160;cm (22.25&#160;in × 7.75&#160;in); <a href="Metropolitan_Museum_of_Art" title="Metropolitan Museum of Art">Metropolitan Museum of Art</a>, New York</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <i><b>Crucifixion and Last Judgement diptych</b></i> (or <i><b>Diptych with Calvary and Last Judgement</b></i>)<sup id="cite_ref-v362_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-v362-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> consists of two small painted panels attributed to the <a href="Early_Netherlandish_painting" title="Early Netherlandish painting">Early Netherlandish</a> artist <a href="Jan_van_Eyck" title="Jan van Eyck">Jan van Eyck</a>, with areas finished by unidentified followers or members of his workshop. Based on technique and the figures' style of dress, the panels are thought to have been executed in the early 1430s, although some art historians have suggested dates as early as 1420. It is one of the early <a href="Northern_Renaissance" title="Northern Renaissance">Northern Renaissance</a> <a href="Panel_painting" title="Panel painting">oil on panel</a> masterpieces, renowned for its unusually complex and highly detailed <a href="Iconography" title="Iconography">iconography</a>, and the technical skill evident in its completion. The <a href="Diptych" title="Diptych">diptych</a> was executed in a miniature format; the panels are just 56.5&#160;cm (22.2&#160;in) high and 19.7&#160;cm (7.8&#160;in) wide, and probably commissioned for personal and private devotion.</p>
<p>The left hand wing depicts the <a href="Crucifixion_of_Jesus" title="Crucifixion of Jesus">Crucifixion</a> and shows Christ's followers grieving in the foreground, soldiers and spectators milling around in the mid-ground and a brutally physical portrayal of three crucified bodies in the upper-ground. The scene is framed against an azure sky with a view of <a href="Jerusalem" title="Jerusalem">Jerusalem</a> in the distance. The right hand wing contains scenes associated with the <a href="Last_Judgment" title="Last Judgment">Last Judgement</a>: a hellscape at its base, the resurrected awaiting judgement in the centre-ground, and a representation of <a href="Christ_in_Majesty" title="Christ in Majesty">Christ in Majesty</a> flanked by a <a href="Deesis" title="Deesis">Great Deësis</a> of saints, <a href="Apostles" title="Apostles" class="mw-redirect">apostles</a>, clergy, virgins and nobility in the upper section.</p>
<p>Portions of the work contain Greek, Latin and Hebrew inscriptions.<sup id="cite_ref-Met_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Met-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> The original <a href="Gilding" title="Gilding">gilt</a> frames contain Biblical passages in Latin drawn from the <a href="Books_of_the_Bible" title="Books of the Bible">books</a> of <a href="Book_of_Isaiah" title="Book of Isaiah">Isaiah</a>, <a href="Book_of_Deuteronomy" title="Book of Deuteronomy">Deutoronomy</a> and <a href="Book_of_Revelation" title="Book of Revelation">Revelation</a>. According to a date written in Russian on their reverse, the panels were <a href="Transfer_of_panel_paintings" title="Transfer of panel paintings">transferred to canvas</a> supports in 1867. Their earliest surviving mention appears in 1841, when it was believed they were wings of a lost <a href="Triptych" title="Triptych">triptych</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-SM144_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SM144-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> The panels were acquired by the <a href="Metropolitan_Museum_of_Art" title="Metropolitan Museum of Art">Metropolitan Museum of Art</a> in 1933 while attributed to Jan's brother <a href="Hubert_van_Eyck" title="Hubert van Eyck">Hubert</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup> There have been significant difficulties in dating the work. Some art historians believe the panels are late works by van Eyck and finished after his death. Others hold that the diptych was executed around the early 1420s and attribute the weaker passages to van Eyck's relative inexperience as a younger painter.<sup id="cite_ref-B86_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-B86-6"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-B89_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-B89-7"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
